04590nam a22006135i 9780822393344DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223933447 a10.1515/97808223933442doi  a(DE-B1597)553303  a(OCoLC)709610931  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aH61b.I443 2011 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a300.122200aImmanuel Wallerstein and the Problem of the World :bSystem, Scale, Culture /cDavid Palumbo-Liu, Nirvana Tanoukhi, Bruce Robbins. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b16 photographs, 2 tables, 2 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction The Most Important Thing Happening -- tThe Modern World-System -- tBlaming the System -- tWorld-Systems Analysis, Evolutionary Theory, Weltliteratur -- tThe Scale of World Literature -- tThe Space of the World -- tCartographies of Connection -- tWhat Is a Poem? -- tThe Legal System of International Human Rights -- tRationality and World-Systems Analysis -- tThinking about the "Humanities" -- tThe Twilight of Capital? -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this collection of essays, leading cultural theorists consider the meaning and implications of world-scale humanist scholarship by engaging with Immanuel Wallerstein's world-systems analysis. The renowned sociologist developed his influential critical framework to explain the historical and continuing exploitation of the rest of the world by the West. World-systems analysis reflects Wallerstein's conviction that understanding global inequality requires thinking on a global scale. Humanists have often criticized his theory as insufficiently attentive to values and objects of knowledge such as culture, agency, difference, subjectivity, and the local. The editors of this collection do not deny the validity of those criticisms; instead, they offer Wallerstein's world-systems analysis as a well-developed vision of the world scale for humanists to think with and against. Scholars of comparative literature, gender, geography, history, law, race, and sociology consider what thinking on the world scale might mean for particular disciplinary practices, knowledge formations, and objects of study. Several essays offer broader reflections on what is at stake for the study of culture in decisions to adopt or reject world-scale thinking. In a brief essay, Immanuel Wallerstein situates world-systems analysis vis-à-vis the humanities.Contributors. Gopal Balakrishnan, Tani E. Barlow, Neil Brenner, Richard E. Lee, Franco Moretti, David Palumbo-Liu, Bruce Robbins, Helen Stacy, Nirvana Tanoukhi, Immanuel Wallerstein, Kären Wigen  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aHistoryxPhilosophy. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticism. 0aSocial sciencesxPhilosophy. 0aSociologyxPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh1 aLee, Richard E.1 aMoretti, Franco1 aPalumbo-Liu, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRobbins, Bruce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTanoukhi, Nirvana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393344zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393344423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822393344.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles